Week 44 unfolded as a study in how much can change when the clock does not seem to move. On the surface, the Democracy Clock held at 7:59 p.m., shifting only a tenth of a minute. Yet beneath that still face, power continued to gather in familiar places. Law, force, and information were bent further toward the service of one man and his circle, while certain institutions pushed back in narrow, defined ways. It was a week in which the state\'92s coercive tools were used more openly against immigrants, transgender people, and political critics, even as Congress and some courts tried to pry open the record of elite abuse. The pattern was not one of sudden collapse. It was the slow tightening of a system that has learned how to harden itself while leaving just enough space for the language of democracy to remain.\
\
At the end of the previous period, the public time on the Democracy Clock stood at 7:59 p.m. It remains there now, with only a fractional movement that does not change the visible hour. That apparent stasis hides the fact that thirty traits edged closer to midnight. The clock did not jump because the week brought no single, decisive break in the constitutional order. Instead, it brought a dense layering of actions that deepened trends already in motion: law as a weapon, security forces as instruments of political will, a civil service remade along ideological lines, and citizenship stratified by identity. Against this, Congress\'92s near-unanimous demand for the Epstein files, and a handful of judicial rulings, provided countervailing force. They did not reverse the drift, but they kept the hands from leaping forward.\
\
The clearest expression of law turned into a weapon came through the Department of Justice. President Trump directed Attorney General Pam Bondi to investigate named Democratic figures mentioned in Epstein-related documents, including a former president and senior economic officials. This was not a broad inquiry into systemic wrongdoing. It was a list of political opponents. At the same time, he ordered a new investigation into the Epstein case itself, after years of dismissing it as a hoax. That timing mattered. The House and Senate were moving, with rare unity, to force the release of Epstein-related records. By reopening the case, the White House created a pretext to argue that disclosure would prejudice an \'93ongoing investigation.\'94 Law became a shield for some and a sword for others. The Justice Department\'92s choices no longer read as neutral enforcement. They read as the legal arm of a personal project.\
\
That pattern was reinforced in the prosecution of former FBI director James Comey. In Virginia, a federal magistrate judge found \'93profound investigative missteps\'94 in the case, including false statements of law to the grand jury by interim U.S. Attorney Lindsey Halligan, a Trump appointee. The judge ordered all grand jury materials turned over to the defense. Later filings revealed something more stark. Halligan had submitted an indictment that the full grand jury had never seen or voted on, with only a foreperson and one other member present. This was not a technical error. It was a breach of the constitutional requirement that serious federal charges rest on a grand jury\'92s independent judgment. The court\'92s response showed that some safeguards still function. But the fact that such a filing reached that stage at all showed how far prosecutorial power can be bent when loyalty, not law, is the main test.\
