Elsewhere, the Justice Department signaled a different kind of favoritism. Officials entered settlement talks with Michael Flynn over his $50 million claim against the government, despite a judge having dismissed his lawsuit. Flynn, a pardoned ally, was now in line not only for legal absolution but for possible financial redress. In Ohio, Trump pardoned Charles Scott, a white-collar offender convicted of stock manipulation, after only two weeks in jail. Prosecutors warned that such clemency undermined deterrence and suggested that connections, not conduct, determined outcomes. At the same time, a House Ethics report concluded that former representative Matt Gaetz had likely paid a homeless 17-year-old for sex, yet the Justice Department had not brought charges. The contrast between aggressive pursuit of some targets and leniency toward others traced a clear line. Law was harsh when it served the regime\'92s story, and soft when it touched its friends.\
