Immigration enforcement became the most visible arena where force was turned inward. In Charlotte, North Carolina, the Department of Homeland Security launched \'93Operation Charlotte\'92s Web\'94 after local police refused to honor immigration detainers without judicial warrants. Over a weekend, Border Patrol and ICE teams swept through neighborhoods, business districts, and areas near churches, arresting at least 81 people in one account and 130 in another. Videos showed masked agents in unmarked cars detaining people in parking lots and outside stores, including at least one U.S. citizen and a teenage grocery worker. Car windows were smashed. Families scattered. The operation was justified as a hunt for \'93violent criminal illegal aliens,\'94 but court records from a similar Chicago raid, \'93Operation Midway Blitz,\'94 showed that more than 97 percent of those detained there had no criminal convictions. The pattern was clear. These were not targeted arrests of dangerous individuals. They were sweeps designed to send a message.\
