That message was aimed not only at immigrants but at local governments. Charlotte and other North Carolina cities had adopted policies limiting cooperation with federal immigration detainers. In response, Border Patrol units were deployed far from the border, into Raleigh, Durham, and Charlotte, in what community groups saw as an attempt to destabilize and intimidate. A judge in Chicago reprimanded a Border Patrol official for attacks on peaceful protesters, reminding him that the agency could not simply assault demonstrators. In Charlotte, two protesters outside a DHS office were arrested during demonstrations against the raids. Local leaders, including the governor and mayor, condemned the operations as fear-mongering. San Diego\'92s city council, watching these developments, advanced an ordinance requiring federal agents to obtain warrants before entering non-public areas of city facilities. Federal power was being used to punish sanctuary jurisdictions. Some localities began to build legal walls in response.\
