The same week, the machinery of detention was turned in a quieter but more lethal way. On October 3, the Department of Veterans Affairs had abruptly terminated its agreement to process medical claims for ICE detainees. By mid-November, the consequences were visible. ICE described the situation as an \'93absolute emergency.\'94 Detainees in California filed a class action lawsuit, detailing cases of denied insulin, halted cancer treatments, and missed dialysis. The VA had signed no-bid contracts on October 25 to replace its services, but the new systems were not yet working. People in federal custody were left without essential care. At the same time, the Center to Advance Security in America sued the VA for failing to respond to a FOIA request about its role in detainee medical claims. The combination of abrupt policy change, opaque contracting, and stonewalled records painted a picture of an administrative state willing to let vulnerable people suffer in the dark.\
