The orders did not stop at records. Executive Order 14183 banned most transgender individuals from enlisting in the military and ordered the discharge of those already serving. It cut off gender-affirming medical care in the military health system and imposed discharge codes that would follow people into civilian life, affecting employment and veterans\'92 benefits. Executive Order 14187 threatened federal funding for hospitals that provided gender-affirming care to youth, pushing clinics to close and insurers to deny coverage. Federal guidance to military-base schools led to the removal of LGBTQ- and race-related books and increased legal risk for educators who used correct names or pronouns. Housing guidance based on \'93biological sex\'94 meant transgender women were turned away from women\'92s shelters and sent to men\'92s facilities. New prison rules transferred transgender women to men\'92s prisons, authorized male guards to conduct pat-downs, and used solitary confinement as the default response to reported threats. Funding was cut for the \'93Press 3\'94 option on the 988 suicide hotline, which had served over a million LGBTQ youth. Across health, housing, education, prisons, and data, the state built a lattice of rules that made transgender life more precarious.\
