Foreign policy and private gain intertwined in ways that further blurred the line between public duty and personal interest. The Trump Organization entered talks to develop a Trump-branded property in Saudi Arabia as part of a government-owned real estate project. At the same time, President Trump confirmed the sale of F-35 stealth jets to Saudi Arabia, despite objections from Israel and concerns within U.S. intelligence agencies about technology leakage to China. He designated Saudi Arabia a major non-NATO ally, a status that brings defense and trade benefits, and announced $1 trillion in deals during Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman\'92s visit. In the Oval Office, he praised MBS\'92s human rights record and dismissed U.S. intelligence findings that the crown prince had ordered the murder of journalist Jamal Khashoggi, calling Khashoggi \'93extremely controversial.\'94 At a Kennedy Center event, he promised Saudi officials expedited military sales, suggesting that standard approval processes could be bypassed. The pattern was stark. When foreign money flowed toward the president\'92s business and political network, security assessments and human rights concerns were pushed aside.\
