The economic story of the week ran on two tracks. On one, technocratic agencies like the EPA and FDA continued to issue rules and guidance on air quality, pesticides, medical devices, and drug access. These actions, while dense and technical, showed that parts of the administrative state still functioned in a rule-bound, evidence-based way. On the other track, the administration\'92s own economic narrative drifted further from the data. Unemployment rose to 4.4 percent, the highest since 2021, and inflation climbed above 3 percent. Manufacturing, construction, and transportation sectors showed recession-like conditions, with tariffs on intermediate goods cited as a major constraint. The administration\'92s \'93Liberation Day\'94 tariffs on Chinese imports had raised costs and disrupted supply chains, then were partially rolled back through a maze of exemptions and deferrals, leaving an effective rate of 10.5 percent. Economists had long warned that taxing inputs would harm production efficiency. Senior officials instead blamed former President Biden for beef price spikes and described the job market as in a \'93quiet time,\'94 touting a \'93Golden Age\'94 economy. The gap between official words and lived experience widened.\
