Looking ahead from Week 44, several processes were already in motion. The Justice Department had 30 days to comply with the Epstein Files Transparency Act, even as the White House and Bondi invoked investigations and national security to narrow its reach. Courts would have to decide whether those claims could override Congress\'92s clear command that embarrassment and political sensitivity were not valid grounds for withholding. The class action over detainee medical care would test whether abrupt administrative changes that endanger lives can stand. Transgender service members and air force plaintiffs were pressing their lawsuit over denied pensions and benefits, challenging the legality of the new military policies. In Indiana and Texas, appeals over gerrymandered maps and redistricting pressures would continue. Congress was weighing a 2026 military budget that could reach $1.045 trillion, with more than half of contract dollars flowing to four major arms companies. Each of these decisions was already queued; none required speculation.\
