By the close of Week 44, the Democracy Clock still read 7:59 p.m., but the hour felt more crowded. Law had been used more openly as a tool of punishment and protection. Security forces had been deployed to send messages to cities and communities that defied the executive\'92s will. The civil service had been reshaped in key agencies to reward loyalty and enforce ideology, especially against transgender people and those who defended them. Foreign policy had been steered through the lens of personal business and political gain. Yet Congress had also shown that it could act with near unanimity to demand transparency in a case that touched both parties. Courts had exposed prosecutorial misconduct and blocked racially gerrymandered maps. Local governments had begun to write their own protections against federal overreach. The week matters not because it brought a visible lurch toward midnight, but because it showed how a system can harden around a leader while still leaving just enough room for resistance to claim the language of law. The official time remains 7:59 p.m. The distance to midnight is unchanged on the dial, but the path between them has grown more narrow and more steep.\
